WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.370 --> 00:00:07.440
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab. This is a free,
complete course for the CCNA. If you like

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:12.380
these videos, please subscribe to follow along
with the series. Also, please like and leave

00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:17.130
a comment, and share the video to help spread
this free series of videos. Thanks for your

00:00:17.130 --> 00:00:24.150
help. In this video we will look at JSON,
XML, and YAML. These are known as data serialization

00:00:24.150 --> 00:00:29.360
languages, or data serialization formats.
These allow us to format or structure data

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:35.850
in a standardized way so it can be communicated
between applications. This is covered in exam

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:41.690
topic 6.7, which says you must be able to
interpret JSON encoded data. Note that it

00:00:41.690 --> 00:00:48.839
only mentions JSON, not XML or YAML. So, the
majority of this video will focus on JSON,

00:00:48.839 --> 00:00:53.899
but at the end I will take a bit of time to
compare JSON to two other popular data serialization

00:00:53.899 --> 00:00:55.730
languages, XML and YAML.

00:00:55.730 --> 00:01:01.979
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.
First I’ll briefly introduce data serialization

00:01:01.979 --> 00:01:07.970
and why we need it. Then I’ll cover JSON.
This will be the main part of this video,

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:13.660
and we’ll focus on how to interpret basic
JSON-encoded data. Then I’ll briefly introduce

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:19.821
XML and YAML, so you can compare and contrast
them with JSON. However I won’t spend so

00:01:19.821 --> 00:01:25.220
much time on those two, since they’re not
mentioned in the exam topics list. And make

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:29.730
sure to watch until the end of the video for
a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:33.090
ExSim, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:40.480
So, let’s take a look at what data serialization
is. It is the process of converting data into

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:46.990
a standardized format, or structure, that
can be stored, for example in a file, or transmitted,

00:01:46.990 --> 00:01:53.380
for example over a network, and then be reconstructed
later, perhaps by a different application.

00:01:53.380 --> 00:01:58.630
Why is that useful? It allows the data to
be communicated between applications in a

00:01:58.630 --> 00:02:04.380
way both applications can understand. If one
application is written in Python, and the

00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:09.490
other is written in Java, both languages store
data differently so they need some standard

00:02:09.490 --> 00:02:16.489
format to send data between each other. Data
serialization languages, for example JSON,

00:02:16.489 --> 00:02:22.540
allow us to represent variables with text.
Now, what is a variable? Here are some examples

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:34.120
of variables. Interface name, gigabitethernet1/1.
Status, up. IP address, 192.168.1.1. Netmask,

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:41.329
255.255.255.0. These are four variables. Basically,
variables are containers that store values.

00:02:41.329 --> 00:02:47.560
For example ‘interface_name’ is a container,
and it contains the value ‘gigabitethernet1/1’

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:53.000
inside of it. ‘Status’ is another container,
and inside there is the value ‘up’. So,

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.120
let’s see how data exchanges would work
without the use of a standard data serialization

00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:04.279
format. The client, for example an app trying
to get information from an SDN controller,

00:03:04.279 --> 00:03:10.499
sends a GET message. The server, the controller,
sends those variables directly to the client

00:03:10.499 --> 00:03:15.710
without converting them to a standard format
like JSON. However, the client doesn’t understand

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:20.749
the data it received. The app and the controller
are programs written in different languages

00:03:20.749 --> 00:03:24.279
and they store data differently, they can’t
communicate directly.

00:03:24.279 --> 00:03:31.170
So let’s see how a data serialization language
such as JSON fixes that. The client sends

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:36.720
a GET request. The requested variables are
sent to the API, which converts them to a

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:42.859
standard format, JSON, and sends them over
the network to the client. Because the variables

00:03:42.859 --> 00:03:47.730
are in a standard format that both the client
and the server understand, the client is able

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:53.409
to take those variables and convert them into
its own native format. Now, we haven’t looked

00:03:53.409 --> 00:03:58.799
at any details about how APIs work yet, I
will cover them in the next video. So, this

00:03:58.799 --> 00:04:02.969
process might not be totally clear for you
yet, but I’m sure you can see the benefit

00:04:02.969 --> 00:04:07.530
of having a standard data format like JSON
to allow these two programs to share data

00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:10.629
with each other.

00:04:10.629 --> 00:04:16.769
Now let’s take a look at JSON. JSON, which
stands for JavaScript Object Notation, is

00:04:16.769 --> 00:04:22.180
an open standard file format and data interchange
format, meaning it can be used to store data

00:04:22.180 --> 00:04:27.949
as files or to send data over a network, that
uses human-readable text to store and transmit

00:04:27.949 --> 00:04:33.840
data objects. So, although it’s used to
exchange data between machines, so it must

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:38.680
be easily machine-readable of course, it’s
also quite human-readable. It’s easy for

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:45.500
us to read and understand. It is standardized
in RFC 8259, which you can access at this

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:52.841
URL. Or just do a google search for RFC 8259.
I recommend taking the time to read it. If

00:04:52.841 --> 00:04:57.550
you’re not used to reading technical documentation
like this it might be a bit difficult to understand

00:04:57.550 --> 00:05:03.400
at first, but it’s the best source to really
understand JSON. Anyway, JSON was derived

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:08.050
from JavaScript, but it is language-independent
and many modern programming languages are

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:14.200
able to generate and read JSON data. Note
that REST APIs often use JSON, which is why

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:21.240
Cisco expects you to learn the basics of JSON
for the CCNA exam. In JSON, whitespace is

00:05:21.240 --> 00:05:27.030
insignificant. What does that mean? Well,
I’ll demonstrate with examples later, but

00:05:27.030 --> 00:05:31.430
basically it means that spaces and linebreaks
don’t matter. They don’t change the meaning

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:37.960
of the data. In JSON, there are four primitive
data types. In the next slide I’ll demonstrate

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:43.530
them, but they are string, number, boolean,
and null. In addition, there are two structured

00:05:43.530 --> 00:05:49.919
data types, object and array. Let’s look
at these six data types and see how JSON data

00:05:49.919 --> 00:05:53.190
is actually formatted.

00:05:53.190 --> 00:05:58.580
First up, the primitive data types. A string
is a text value, and it is surrounded by double

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:04.879
quotes. Here are some examples of strings.
Hello. Notice that it is surrounded by double

00:06:04.879 --> 00:06:11.039
quotes. This means it is a string, a series
of alphanumeric characters. These are all

00:06:11.039 --> 00:06:16.389
also strings. So, remember that if it’s
contained within double quotes, it’s a string,

00:06:16.389 --> 00:06:23.539
a simple text value. Next, a number is simply
a numeric value. It is not surrounded by quotes.

00:06:23.539 --> 00:06:29.979
So, 5, 100, or any other number. Note that
the five in the string examples with the double

00:06:29.979 --> 00:06:35.240
quotes is a string, a text value, but the
5 down here without double quotes is a number,

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:42.240
a numeric value. They are different data types.
Next, a boolean is a data type that has only

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:49.340
two possible values. Those are true and false.
Note that they are written without quotes.

00:06:49.340 --> 00:06:55.400
In a networking setting, perhaps on an OSPF-enabled
interface a variable named ‘passive’ would

00:06:55.400 --> 00:07:00.570
have the boolean value ‘true’ if the interface
is passive, and if the interface isn’t passive

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:05.449
the variable would have the boolean value
‘false’. That’s just one example of

00:07:05.449 --> 00:07:11.070
how boolean values could be used. Note that
in the string examples I included “true”

00:07:11.070 --> 00:07:15.509
with double quotes. That isn’t a boolean
value, that’s just the word ‘true’,

00:07:15.509 --> 00:07:21.330
a series of letters. However when written
without double quotes, it is a boolean value.

00:07:21.330 --> 00:07:28.590
Finally, note that they are written all lower-case,
no capital T in true or capital F in false.

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:33.570
The final primitive data type is null, which
represents the intentional absence of any

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:40.539
object value. It’s simply written as null,
lower case n u l l, without quotes. This simply

00:07:40.539 --> 00:07:46.199
means there is no value, it means nothing.
Again, in the string examples I included “null”

00:07:46.199 --> 00:07:51.330
in double quotes. That is a string, because
it is contained within double quotes. It does

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:56.189
not express a null value, it just means the
word ‘null’. Okay, those are the four

00:07:56.189 --> 00:08:01.349
primitive JSON data types. String, number,
boolean, and null.

00:08:01.349 --> 00:08:08.530
Now let’s go on to the structured data types,
there are two. First, an object is an unordered

00:08:08.530 --> 00:08:14.530
list of key-value pairs, basically variables.
Unordered means the order of the variables

00:08:14.530 --> 00:08:20.870
doesn’t matter. Objects are surrounded by
curly brackets. The key, which is basically

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:27.599
the name of the variable, the container, must
be a string. So, it must use double quotes.

00:08:27.599 --> 00:08:33.219
Then the value inside of that variable can
be any valid JSON data type. A string, number,

00:08:33.219 --> 00:08:40.260
boolean, null, object, or array. The key and
the value are separated by a colon, and if

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:45.040
there are multiple key-value pairs in the
object, each pair is separated by a comma.

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:52.310
Okay, let’s look at some examples to help
you visualize it. This is one JSON object.

00:08:52.310 --> 00:08:56.991
Note the curly bracket at the top indicating
the start of the object, and the curly bracket

00:08:56.991 --> 00:09:03.430
closing it at the bottom. Inside there are
five key-value pairs. Before looking at this

00:09:03.430 --> 00:09:09.670
object in more detail, I want to show you
this. This is the exact same object. As I

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:15.970
said before, in JSON whitespace is insignificant,
it has no meaning. Of course, for humans the

00:09:15.970 --> 00:09:21.839
one on the left is easier to read, but computers
don’t care either way.

00:09:21.839 --> 00:09:29.110
So, I’ve colored the keys blue and the values
red. All of this is one JSON object, but let’s

00:09:29.110 --> 00:09:34.910
look at the data type of each individual key
and value. First, the top one. “interface”

00:09:34.910 --> 00:09:40.500
in double quotes, that’s the key. Then notice
a colon separating the key and the value,

00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:46.270
which is “gigabitethernet1/1” in double
quotes. So, the key and value are both strings,

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:51.380
they both have double quotes. Remember that
the key must be a string, but the value can

00:09:51.380 --> 00:09:57.190
be any valid JSON data type. Notice that there
is a comma after as well, because if there

00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:03.279
are multiple key-value pairs in an object,
each pair is separated by a comma. Okay, in

00:10:03.279 --> 00:10:09.300
the next key-value pair under it the key is
“is_up”. It’s a string, of course. Notice

00:10:09.300 --> 00:10:13.810
the colon between the key “is_up” and
the value, which is true, written without

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:20.410
double quotes. That is a boolean. This probably
indicates that the interface status is up,

00:10:20.410 --> 00:10:25.949
because of the value true for the key “is_up”.
Again, notice the comma after this key-value

00:10:25.949 --> 00:10:31.839
pair, because there is another key-value pair
after it. For these next two examples, the

00:10:31.839 --> 00:10:36.529
values are both strings, because they are
contained within double quotes. Notice the

00:10:36.529 --> 00:10:41.380
standard JSON formatting again. The key is
always a string, there is a colon between

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:47.339
the key and value, and there is a comma after
each key-value pair. Now let’s look at the

00:10:47.339 --> 00:10:54.240
final pair. What data type is the value 1000?
It’s a number, a numeric value not contained

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:59.940
in double quotes. And notice that this time
there is no comma after the value. That’s

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:05.370
because it’s the last key-value pair in
this object. Okay, so that’s a basic JSON

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:08.570
object with multiple key-value pairs inside.

00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:14.399
Now, as you can see in the following example,
objects are a valid data type for the value

00:11:14.399 --> 00:11:19.681
of a key-value pair. I’ve colored the curly
brackets to make it a bit easier to see, but

00:11:19.681 --> 00:11:25.250
I want you to pause the video to try to interpret
this data. Find the key value pairs. It’s

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:30.220
important that you get comfortable reading
JSON-formatted data, as it’s clearly stated

00:11:30.220 --> 00:11:36.610
in the CCNA exam. Okay, so this example is
one JSON object, indicated by the red curly

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:42.220
brackets at the top and bottom. Inside of
this object there are two key-value pairs.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:49.190
Here’s one key-value pair. The key is “device”,
a string of course, and the value is an object,

00:11:49.190 --> 00:11:55.290
indicated by the blue curly brackets. So,
we have an object inside of an object. Note

00:11:55.290 --> 00:12:01.269
that objects within objects are called ‘nested
objects’. Now, within that value, the object,

00:12:01.269 --> 00:12:07.420
there are multiple key-value pairs. “name”:”R1”
is a key-value pair, “vendor”:”Cisco”

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:13.800
is a key-value pair, and “model”:”1101”
is a key-value pair. Now down here we have

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:19.200
one more key-value pair, and again the value
is an object, indicated by the purple curly

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:24.850
brackets. And inside of that object there
are again more key-value pairs. I’m keeping

00:12:24.850 --> 00:12:30.270
this fairly easy to read by using indenting
and using line breaks and different colors,

00:12:30.270 --> 00:12:35.839
but keep in mind that JSON data won’t always
look like this. The whitespace is insignificant

00:12:35.839 --> 00:12:40.519
and only used to make it easier for us to
read, but applications themselves don’t

00:12:40.519 --> 00:12:42.750
need this whitespace.

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:49.529
Okay, now there is one more JSON structured
data type to look at, and that is the array.

00:12:49.529 --> 00:12:55.690
An array is a series of values separated by
commas. Note that it’s not a series of key-value

00:12:55.690 --> 00:13:01.480
pairs, that’s an object. It’s just a series
of values. And note that the values don’t

00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:06.269
have to be the same data type. One could be
a string, and another a number, for example.

00:13:06.269 --> 00:13:13.250
So, here I’ve got one JSON object with two
key-value pairs, and both of the values are

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:19.370
arrays. The first array, the value of the
“interfaces” key, lists three interface

00:13:19.370 --> 00:13:25.709
names, with a comma between each of them.
Note that there is no comma after gigabitethernet1/3,

00:13:25.709 --> 00:13:30.870
because it’s the last value. And then the
second array has two values, “Hi” and

00:13:30.870 --> 00:13:37.019
5. Note that “Hi” is a string and 5 is
a number, because it has no double quotes.

00:13:37.019 --> 00:13:41.930
So, as you can see the values don’t necessarily
have to be the same type, although often they

00:13:41.930 --> 00:13:47.209
will be. If you need to, pause the video now
to look at this example and make sure you

00:13:47.209 --> 00:13:52.790
understand it, as well as the previous examples.
Just listening to me talk about JSON won’t

00:13:52.790 --> 00:13:57.990
help you interpret it if you don’t practice
actually looking at and understanding JSON-formatted

00:13:57.990 --> 00:13:59.589
data.

00:13:59.589 --> 00:14:04.660
For reference, here is the output of SHOW
IP INTERFACE BRIEF, and a version of the same

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:11.050
output in JSON. Note that this isn’t actual
JSON output from a Cisco device, I just wrote

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:16.519
this JSON data myself. The point is that,
although SHOW command outputs in the CLI are

00:14:16.519 --> 00:14:20.899
easy for us humans to read, they aren’t
in a format that is easy for computers to

00:14:20.899 --> 00:14:26.829
understand. JSON, on the other hand, is very
easy for computers to understand, and if we

00:14:26.829 --> 00:14:32.120
format the text properly like this it’s
also quite human-readable too. Anyway, pause

00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:37.210
the video if you want to compare this SHOW
command output and the JSON data.

00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:42.420
Okay, so we’ve looked at all of the six
JSON data types. There are four primitive

00:14:42.420 --> 00:14:49.060
data types: string, number, boolean, and null,
and two structured data types: object and

00:14:49.060 --> 00:14:55.500
array. One more point, note that an object
is sometimes called a dictionary. Same thing,

00:14:55.500 --> 00:15:00.589
just a different name, but you should be aware
of it. Okay, that’s all for JSON for now.

00:15:00.589 --> 00:15:05.870
We’ll take a quick look at XML and YAML,
and then in the quiz for today’s video we’ll

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:09.040
get lots of practice interpreting JSON data.

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:17.660
So, here’s XML. XML was developed as a markup
language, but is now used as a general data

00:15:17.660 --> 00:15:21.890
serialization language. You know what a data
serialization language is, but what’s a

00:15:21.890 --> 00:15:27.990
markup language? Markup languages are used
to format text, for example HTML, which you’ve

00:15:27.990 --> 00:15:34.649
probably heard of, is a markup language. XML
is generally less human-readable than JSON,

00:15:34.649 --> 00:15:40.399
although it’s not so difficult to read.
Like JSON, whitespace is insignificant, although

00:15:40.399 --> 00:15:45.240
you’ll often see it displayed with spaces
and line breaks to make it more human-readable.

00:15:45.240 --> 00:15:52.100
XML is also often used by REST APIs, same
as JSON. The general format you need to know

00:15:52.100 --> 00:15:58.699
is this: the key is tagged like this, with
the value in the middle. For example, on Cisco

00:15:58.699 --> 00:16:04.579
IOS you can use a SHOW command, pipe the command
with the FORMAT keyword, and it will display

00:16:04.579 --> 00:16:12.519
it in XML. I used SHOW IP INTERFACE BRIEF,
pipe, FORMAT, and here is the output in XML

00:16:12.519 --> 00:16:17.200
format. I’ve colored the output to make
it easier to see, so I think you can easily

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:24.480
see the keys and values. We have two interfaces,
each marked with ENTRY tags. Within each entry

00:16:24.480 --> 00:16:30.920
we have Interface, IP-address, OK, Method,
Status, and Protocol keys, and the value is

00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:35.960
in the middle of those keys. For example,
here we have an &lt;Interface&gt; tag, with a value

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:43.410
of GigabitEthernet0/0, and then a forward
slash interface tag to close it off.

00:16:43.410 --> 00:16:48.680
And here you can compare the regular SHOW
IP INTERFACE BRIEF output with the XML-formatted

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:54.060
output, without any coloring in the XML this
time. XML is generally thought to be less

00:16:54.060 --> 00:16:58.829
human-readable than JSON, but it’s still
not so hard to read when formatted like this.

00:16:58.829 --> 00:17:04.250
So, that’s all I’ll say about XML. If
you’re familiar with HTML, it looks quite

00:17:04.250 --> 00:17:11.010
similar. Remember basic characteristics like
the key-value pair format for variables using

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:17.280
tags, remember that whitespace is insignificant,
and remember that it’s similar to HTML and

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:22.490
also used by REST APIs. If you want to take
some time to examine this output pause the

00:17:22.490 --> 00:17:25.419
video, but now I’ll move on.

00:17:25.419 --> 00:17:32.420
Finally, let’s take a brief look at YAML.
The name YAML originally meant Yet Another

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:37.840
Markup Language, but to distinguish its purpose
as a data-serialization language rather than

00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:44.040
a markup language, it was repurposed to YAML
Aint Markup Language. That’s known as a

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:50.030
recursive acronym by the way, when the acronym
itself is part of the acronym. YAML is used

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:55.090
by the network automation tool Ansible, which
we’ll cover in another video. It has all

00:17:55.090 --> 00:17:59.990
sorts of other uses too, of course, but its
use in Ansible is relevant to our current

00:17:59.990 --> 00:18:07.429
topic, network automation. YAML is very human-readable,
and whitespace is significant, unlike JSON

00:18:07.429 --> 00:18:13.250
and XML. So, indentation is very important.
We aren’t free to format the text however

00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:20.179
we want. YAML files start with three hyphens,
and one hyphen is used to indicate a list.

00:18:20.179 --> 00:18:27.010
Key value pairs are represented as key colon
value. There are more rules to YAML, of course,

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:32.711
but I’ll leave it there. Here’s an example
of YAML. This is the same SHOW IP INTERFACE

00:18:32.711 --> 00:18:40.690
BRIEF data I showed you in JSON and XML. It
looks quite simple compared to JSON and XML.

00:18:40.690 --> 00:18:46.909
And for comparison, here it is next to JSON.
As you can see, both languages are quite human-readable,

00:18:46.909 --> 00:18:51.280
and they’re also used by applications to
communicate data. So, that’s all I’ll

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:56.351
say about YAML. You don’t need to know it
or XML as much as you need to know JSON, but

00:18:56.351 --> 00:19:01.400
you should know basic things such as the fact
that whitespace is significant in YAML, and

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:06.049
that it’s used in Ansible, because we’ll
be studying Ansible in a future video.

00:19:06.049 --> 00:19:12.159
Here’s what we covered in this video. I
gave a basic introduction to data serialization

00:19:12.159 --> 00:19:18.030
and why we need it. Basically, it’s to provide
a standard data format so applications can

00:19:18.030 --> 00:19:24.140
communicate the data with each other. Then
I introduced JSON, XML, and YAML, focusing

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:27.860
primarily on JSON because it’s the one you
really need to know for the CCNA. Now, in

00:19:27.860 --> 00:19:34.050
today’s quiz I will give more questions
than usual so you can practice reading and

00:19:34.050 --> 00:19:40.190
interpreting JSON data. And make sure to watch
until the end of the quiz for a bonus question

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:46.340
from Boson Software’s ExSim, the best practice
exams for the CCNA. Okay, let’s go to quiz

00:19:46.340 --> 00:19:49.240
question 1.

00:19:49.240 --> 00:19:54.371
In which of the following data serialization
languages is whitespace significant? Pause

00:19:54.371 --> 00:19:58.690
the video now to select the best answer.

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:08.480
Okay, the answer is B, YAML. In JSON and XML
whitespace is not significant, it has no meaning.

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:13.450
However in YAML whitespace is significant,
so things like indentation are very important.

00:20:13.450 --> 00:20:17.570
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:20:17.570 --> 00:20:22.580
Which of the following data serialization
languages formats key-value pairs like this?

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:30.630
Key, value, and then forward slash key. Pause
the video now to select the best answer.

00:20:30.630 --> 00:20:40.150
Okay, the answer is C, XML. XML uses HTML-like
tags like this to indicate key-value pairs.

00:20:40.150 --> 00:20:44.500
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:49.600
Which of the following is NOT a valid JSON
data type? Pause the video now to select the

00:20:49.600 --> 00:20:53.039
best answer.

00:20:53.039 --> 00:21:01.880
Okay, the answer is E, key. Although JSON
defines key-value pairs, key isn’t actually

00:21:01.880 --> 00:21:08.200
a data type. All keys must be strings, and
string is a valid data type. Okay, let’s

00:21:08.200 --> 00:21:11.750
go to question 4.

00:21:11.750 --> 00:21:16.590
Examine the JSON-formatted data. Which of
the following statements is true? Pause the

00:21:16.590 --> 00:21:20.390
video now to select the best answer.

00:21:20.390 --> 00:21:29.030
Okay, the answer is C, there are too many
commas. Here I’ve highlighted the extra

00:21:29.030 --> 00:21:34.789
comma. A comma is required between separate
key-value pairs in an object, but you should

00:21:34.789 --> 00:21:42.460
not put a comma after the last key-value pair.
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:21:42.460 --> 00:21:47.179
Examine the JSON-formatted data. Which of
the following statements is true? Pause the

00:21:47.179 --> 00:21:51.700
video now to select the best answer.

00:21:51.700 --> 00:22:00.179
Okay, the answer is B, the value of “ip_interfaces”
is an array. Now, within that array there

00:22:00.179 --> 00:22:05.660
are multiple objects, but as these square
brackets indicate, the value itself is an

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:12.890
array, that’s the JSON data type. Okay,
let’s go to question 6.

00:22:12.890 --> 00:22:18.100
Which of the following is an example of valid
JSON-formatted data? Pause the video now to

00:22:18.100 --> 00:22:21.799
select the best answer.

00:22:21.799 --> 00:22:30.590
Okay, the answer is D. Let me point out the
errors in the others. In A, there is a comma

00:22:30.590 --> 00:22:36.419
after the “interfaces” key. It should
be a colon. In B, there is a colon after this

00:22:36.419 --> 00:22:42.600
value 5. A colon should only be used between
the key and value of a key-value pair, it

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:51.600
is not valid here. And in C, there is a missing
comma between gigabitethernet1/1 and gigabitethernet1/2.

00:22:51.600 --> 00:22:56.980
If multiple values are listed in an array,
there must be a comma between each of them.

00:22:56.980 --> 00:23:05.380
There are no problems with D, it is valid
JSON data. Okay, let’s go to question 7.

00:23:05.380 --> 00:23:10.090
Examine the JSON-formatted data. Which of
the following statements is true? Pause the

00:23:10.090 --> 00:23:14.720
video now to select the best answer.

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:23.150
Okay, the answer is A, the value of “is_up”
is a boolean. I’ve highlighted it here.

00:23:23.150 --> 00:23:28.770
It’s true, written without double quotes,
so it is a boolean value. Booleans can be

00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:36.860
true or false, and they are written without
quotes. Okay, let’s go to question 8.

00:23:36.860 --> 00:23:41.450
Examine the JSON-formatted data. Which of
the following statements is true? Pause the

00:23:41.450 --> 00:23:46.059
video now to select the best answer.

00:23:46.059 --> 00:23:54.910
Okay, the answer is D, it is valid JSON data.
No comma or curly brackets are missing, and

00:23:54.910 --> 00:24:01.090
whitespace is insignificant in JSON, so this
is validly formatted. We often use indentation

00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:05.880
and line breaks to make it easier to read,
but whitespace like that is unnecessary and

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:12.860
doesn’t have any meaning in JSON. Okay,
let’s go to question 9.

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:17.990
Examine the JSON-formatted data. Which of
the following statements is true? I think

00:24:17.990 --> 00:24:23.140
this question will be a bit more of a challenge.
Make sure each opening curly bracket has a

00:24:23.140 --> 00:24:28.279
closing curly bracket, each opening square
bracket has a closing square bracket, each

00:24:28.279 --> 00:24:35.919
string has double quotes, etc. Pause the video
to select the best answer.

00:24:35.919 --> 00:24:44.399
Okay, the answer is C, a square bracket is
missing. The value of the “routes” key

00:24:44.399 --> 00:24:49.870
is an array, it has an opening square bracket,
but in the example on the left there is no

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:54.710
closing square bracket for that array. Again,
make sure to check carefully that each opening

00:24:54.710 --> 00:25:01.480
bracket has a closing bracket. Let’s go
to question 10.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:06.100
Examine the JSON-formatted data. Which of
the following statements is true? Pause the

00:25:06.100 --> 00:25:10.760
video now to select the best answer.

00:25:10.760 --> 00:25:19.460
Okay, the answer is A, it is valid JSON data.
There are no missing curly brackets or square

00:25:19.460 --> 00:25:25.460
brackets, and the value of “dhcp4” is
a string, not a boolean. Okay, I hope this

00:25:25.460 --> 00:25:29.370
practice was helpful for you. That’s all
for the quiz. Now let’s take a look at a

00:25:29.370 --> 00:25:33.796
bonus question from Boson Software’s ExSim
for CCNA.

